    "en": "Generators & yield: Lazy Sequences on Demand",
    "ta": "ஜெனரேட்டர்கள் & yield: தேவைக்கேற்ப சோம்பல் வரிசைகள்"
  },
  "description": {
    "en": "Learn how generators produce values lazily with yield, generator expressions, and why they are memory-efficient for large datasets.",
    "ta": "yield மூலம் ஜெனரேட்டர்கள் எவ்வாறு சோம்பலாக மதிப்புகளை உருவாக்குகின்றன, ஜெனரேட்டர் expressions, பெரிய தரவுத்தொகுப்புகளுக்கு நினைவக-திறன் ஆகியவற்றைக் கற்றுக்கொள்ளுங்கள்."
  },
  "xp_reward": 70,
  "story_variants": {
    "en": "## Vaathiyaar's Magic Tap\n\nVaathiyaar turns on a tap. \"This tap doesn't store all the water in a bucket first — it gives you water **on demand**, one drop at a time. That's what a generator does with values!\"\n\n### List vs Generator\n\n| Feature | List | Generator |\n|---------|------|------------|\n| Memory | Stores ALL items | Stores ONE at a time |\n| Creation | `[x for x in range(1M)]` | `(x for x in range(1M))` |\n| Speed | Fast access by index | Must iterate sequentially |\n| Reusable | Yes | No — exhausted after one pass |\n\n### The yield Keyword\n\n```python\ndef countdown(n):\n    while n > 0:\n        yield n    # pause here, give n, resume later\n        n -= 1\n\nfor num in countdown(3):\n    print(num)  # 3, 2, 1\n```\n\n> **Key Concept:** `yield` pauses the function and returns a value. When `next()` is called again, it resumes right where it left off. The function's local variables are preserved between yields!"
  },
